Document Brocade Networking plug-in

The driver is now part of Networking, update documentation URL
and document how to use it.

commit_message:
Autogenerate config tools: Allow line wrapping

The options have previously been written as "option=default". Let's
add spaces like "opt = default" to allow line wrapping.

Change-Id: Ie1fa1161adfb289feaf0d4bf801866a2dded5cd8
Closes-Bug: #1196187

commit_message:
Show more sensible error messages during Service Creation.

If Metadata Repository is not available, show more concise error
messages.
Also refactor wrapper for handling Metadata Repository exceptions,
thus allowing to throw-away some boilerplate code.

Change-Id: I6acd94bf2ca397941f45bc4c8d9e9fe74678b5ee
Closes-bug: #1263463

commit_message:
Show results of last task without requring user to lookup UUID

Currently to view the results of the last task/benchmark a user must
list tasks, copy a UUID, then query for that UUID. This commit alows the
user to specify 'last' instead of a UUID to retrieve the results of the
last task.

Change-Id: I8ffe1bb8d925a6a114e4dd12be2f1af13e1bfced

commit_message:
Environments synchronization

Because of some user activity devops database could
contain outdated data. The review adds new 'sync' command
that allows to synchronize devops database and
libvirt domains.
Synchronization include:
- Undefining domains that devops do not know about
- Removing records from devops database if
there are no such domains

Change-Id: I2331174a60f581f24219ae124da1cf5fe4ca3f09

commit_message:
Do not use python built-ins as variable names

`property' and `exit' in python are built-in classes, we should not
use them as variable name.

Change-Id: If02d6ac2bd3bd4f1d4bb3e5a2589421e12a4b8e6

commit_message:
Update dependencies for openstack/common/rpc

Update existing modules and add sslutils.py and versionutils.py

sslutils is used in openstack/common/rpc/impl_kombu
versionutils is needed in openstack/common/rpc/impl_kombu

Oslo version: 8388e97e7e98f3b5501c3ed10664f9c7dd527dff

Change-Id: Ia0a396d84e829487d2ba9e3bdcc60fcc27d8f692

commit_message:
Refactor the way benchmark engine returns its results

This patch adds the 'idle_time' parameter to all dictionaries that the
benchmark engine may return as its result in different places of code
(so that the output format is always the same). Here we also remove
several redundant except clauses which are not likely to be ever entered
and also slightly refactor the _run_scenario_loop method to avoid code
duplicate.

Blueprint benchmark-engine-refactoring

Change-Id: I15d5dd8e1d2035174cbc0c13a5558a7c6ffce300

commit_message:
Relocated step to restart Neutron plug-in agent

Relocated step to restart Neutron plug-in agent from section for
plug-in configuration to after completion of Neutron configuration.
This change allows the plug-in agent to read all configured values
from neutron.conf required for proper start and operation.

Implemented more generic phrasing with the Open vSwitch plug-in
agent as an example.

Change-Id: Ie6a614683271674678fc4d44f88c3fe47bb3b473
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1264163

commit_message:
Enable H233/H301/H302 tests that are ignored at the moment

  * H233 use of print operator
  * H301 one import per line
  * H302 import only modules

Change-Id: I752c3c117e2575b30cc96d68c18df365d595588e
Closes-bug: #1263535

[{'created': '2013-12-24 08:23:56.000000000', 'message': 'Fix use the fact that empty sequences are false.

For sequences(strings, lists, tuples), as PEP 8 Programming
Recommendations:
Yes: if not seq:
     if seq:
No: if len(seq)
    if not len(seq)
So, fix the wrong used in keystone.

Change-Id: Ieb2c90b7f87b54361a2c291a838550227fde9fbe
Closes-Bug: #1156472
'}, {'created': '2013-12-28 09:27:29.000000000', 'message': "Fix use the fact that empty sequences are false.

For sequences(strings, lists, tuples), in order to consistent with
pep8 recommendations, 'if len(seq)' should be replaced with 'if seq',
and 'if not len(seq)' should be replaced with 'if not seq'.

Change-Id: Ieb2c90b7f87b54361a2c291a838550227fde9fbe
Closes-Bug: #1156472
"}]
commit_message:
Fix use the fact that empty sequences are false.

For sequences(strings, lists, tuples), in order to consistent with
pep8 recommendations, 'if len(seq)' should be replaced with 'if seq',
and 'if not len(seq)' should be replaced with 'if not seq'.

Change-Id: Ieb2c90b7f87b54361a2c291a838550227fde9fbe
Closes-Bug: #1156472

lifeless: I didn't find filtering in testtools that was directly reusable, but I was glad to learn of the __unittest marker variable and am using it in the same way as testtools to identify frames associated with testing frameworks.

Please correct me if I'm wrong, but the filtering in testtools appears to be limited to the testtools.content.TracebackContent callable and it only filters frames from the top of the traceback.  Filtering from the top is easier since all that is required is skipping over frames until the desired start point.  Filtering from the bottom would seem to require the approach implemented by FilteredTraceback (in this change), since tb_next is a read-only property.  Or is there a better option that you would suggest?"}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2013-10-27 15:56:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-27 16:54:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Works for me

commit_message:
Add post-mortem debug option for tests

Post-mortem debugging, the ability to drop into a debugger with the
execution state that triggered the exception, is very useful in
diagnosing failure conditions.  Our previous test runner, nose,
provided the ability to enable post-mortem debugging on test
failures (via --pdb-failure) and errors (via --pdb).  testr
lacks these options at present, so this change adds support
for enabling post-mortem debugging via an environment variable.
All test-triggered exceptions will result in a post-mortem debugger
being invoked if OS_POST_MORTEM_DEBUG is set to "1" or "True".

Implements: blueprint neutron-pm-debug-on-test-failure
Change-Id: Iddbe1335b059d062c0286df2ad27aef7728461b7

commit_message:
Add apache2 license header to appropriate files for enabling H102

Apache2 license says that each source file should include the license
header. However, some non empty files don't have it. And we already have
a hacking rule (H102) for this.
This commit fixes them and enables the rule.

Change-Id: I68fa0e1ee43ed28d6b470c0ffff963c095be8283

I concern that traceback is lost or not.

although  traceback is output by "log.error" 
in glance log file, is it output in Jenkins result?

if my understand is incorrect, let me know.

example:
pattern A:
----------------------------------------
vagrant@precise64:~$ cat test7.py
def abc():
  a[0]

try:
  abc()
except Exception as err:
  msg="%s" % err
  raise

vagrant@precise64:~$ python test7.py
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "test7.py", line 5, in <module>
    abc()
  File "test7.py", line 2, in abc
    a[0]
NameError: global name 'a' is not defined
----------------------------------------------

->Traceback is'nt lost.
  "abc" function is cause by trace back at a glance.

pattern B)
-------------------------------------
vagrant@precise64:~$ cat test7.py
def abc():
  a[0]

try:
  abc()
except Exception as err:
  msg="%s" % err
  raise Exception(msg)

vagrant@precise64:~$ python test7.py
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "test7.py", line 8, in <module>
    raise Exception(msg)
Exception: global name 'a' is not defined
------------------------------------------

->Traceback is lost.'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-11-19 07:11:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

In Python 2.x,  we can get traceback by sys.exc_info()
and set third argument of raise statement. 
 - http://docs.python.org/2/reference/simple_stmts.html#raise

thanks

Example)
-------------------------------------------------
vagrant@precise64:~$ cat test7.py
import sys

class GlanceException(Exception):
    """
    Base Glance Exception

    To correctly use this class, inherit from it and define
    a 'message' property. That message will get printf'd
    with the keyword arguments provided to the constructor.
    """
    message = "test"

    def __init__(self, message=None, *args, **kwargs):
        if not message:
            message = self.message
        try:
            message = message % kwargs
        except Exception:
            if _FATAL_EXCEPTION_FORMAT_ERRORS:
                raise
            else:
                # at least get the core message out if something happened
                pass

        super(GlanceException, self).__init__(message)

def abc():
  a[0]

try:
  abc()
except Exception as err:
  t=sys.exc_info()[2]
  msg="%s" % err
  raise GlanceException(msg),None,t

commit_message:
Propagate backend exception on fetch

If a request to the backend fails partway through, it's possible that
the Exception raised is assumed to be an issue in glance itself. Thus
any request made to glance which fails in this way may not be terminated
correctly (which can lead to nova hanging). This passes the exception up
the call stack appropriately to terminate the request gracefully.

addresses bug 1252277

Change-Id: I343a04a9a12a184bc8be3c9ba7aeddf0443472b1

commit_message:
Glancelient should not check status of image

Glanceclient should not check status
for updating an image, glance image-update cli is checking
th image status in glance client this is the responsibility of
glance api.This patch goal is to remove the condition checking for
image status in glance-client.

fixes: bug #1240462
Change-Id: I47f8d9af6a1a7d78356319775d6b536b555c0c0b

commit_message:
Delete instance system metadata in db.instance_destroy()

We should delete instance_system_metadata in db.instance_destroy()
If we don't do this we will get issues:
instance_system_metadata records won't be soft deleted, so we won't
be able to purge this table or even to use db archiving

Change-Id: I5223055e560830f2f2306dc94601992b8bb856a5
Closes-bug: #1250993

commit_message:
Fix configuring ml2 problem in RedHat

In RedHat RDO, it package ml2 and its config as a separate package
named openstack-neutron-ml2, we should make sure to install it before
configuring ml2_conf.ini.

Change-Id: Ie18f68e01110e1f1f27f3ec6adc00f224617df1d
Closes-bug: #1264205

commit_message:
port test_quotas into v3 part2

this ports test_quotas and corresponding clients into nova v3 api.
nova v3 api doesn't support security-groups. Due to the bug 1186354,
currently just remove some related tests, and these tests  will be
rework after that bug is fixed.
this removes the injected_files, injected_file_content_bytes and
injected_file_path_bytes in the v3 tests, because these have been
hidden in nova v3 api.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Ic60e33d798275c331e79a4600f1a52b27b79db2a

Sync oslo db.sqlalchemy.utils to nova

Changes from oslo-incubator:
===============================

Change I9c441d26: Use single meta when change column type
Change Id6cf7b12: Helper function to sanitize db url credentials

Change I292ec445: Change sqlalchemy/utils.py mode back to 644

Change Ie54fcd5d: Migrate sqlalchemy utils from Nova

commit_message:
Move policy check of confirm/revert_resize and resize to api layer

This patch moves "compute:resize/confirm_resize/revert_resize" to
api layer for ec2 and nova api v2, and uses
"compute:v3:servers:resize/confirm_resize/revert_resize" for nova
api v3. Also removes policy check from compute api. And give default
rules for v3 policy check.

Partially implements bp v3-api-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: I4bb69db16cbe48a67db7507e64639034ce4ce856

commit_message:
platform independence for test_virt unit tests

Uses mock to avoid direct use of /proc file system
in the unit tests. This makes these tests platform
independent.

Change-Id: I21986681a9a1a6db516957246b71d7fd2055d44b

commit_message:
Don't use deprecated module commands

The commands module was deprecated since version 2.6 and it has been
removed in Python 3.

See http://docs.python.org/2/library/commands#module-commands

Closes-Bug: #1248216
Change-Id: I0ae40c7683ca58ede75f493d020e5c80a6434fef

commit_message:
Add core_authorizer with 'compute:' as the scope of core api in v3

For distinguishing core and extension api. Use different namespace
for policy. The policy of core api will be 'compute:v3:extension_name'.

Partial implements bp v3-api-core-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia8e6d4ea91b56ac67721d42b44b510fba0432582

commit_message:
Handle inject failures for mandatory files correctly

The logic for the inject failure handling was incorrect, in that it
was treating injection of mandatory files as being a non-fatal error.

I've also moved the static class method to being just a normal method
because it was causing me testing errors once I fixed the error
reporting and I can't see a good reason for it to be a class method.

Change-Id: I77f87cddb8634782947cb3aea1953f169ef53cfd
Closes-Bug: 1221985

commit_message:
Make _get_utf8_value Python3 compliant

This function now works with both Python 2 and 3.

Thanks to Victor Stinner for helping with this.

Change-Id: I1644db7705f7818471d06fb74a4b9a91956e6b58

commit_message:
Fix for qemu-nbd hang (WORKINPROGRESS)

PLEASE DON'T REVIEW/MERGE

NBD device once used seem to run into intermittent trouble when
used with mount repeatedly.

Partial-Bug: #1254890

commit_message:
port some servers tests into nova v3 part2

this ports test_servers, test_create_server and test_multiple_create
into nova v3 api, and also ports corresponding client.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Icc2de969a415ef2e2cb85a409b6cdcc47c908322

commit_message:
Fix validation issues

Fix various issues found by xmllint run:
* Fix location to common.ent
* Add namespace declarations to content.ent
* Fix URLs
* replace xmlns="http://wadl:docbook.org/ns/wadl:docbook"
  which gives an "Invalid URL error" with proper
  xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"

Command used:
xmllint --noent --noout --schema \
http://docs.rackspace.com/rackbook/wadl.xsd *.wadl

Change-Id: I1acd975e3cf1ac38be17ad2b382430ba5374a014

Change-Id: I9ebfdde03c0f25cadd1323de9863a230d8058f4e
'}, {'created': '2013-12-17 23:01:13.000000000', 'message': 'Fix variable passed to driver module

'}, {'created': '2013-12-21 22:01:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix variable passed to driver module

If a create project request is sent to keystone with no enabled field set,

but because we are passing the wrong variable to the driver creation

commit_message:
Fix variable passed to driver module

If a create project request is sent to keystone with no enabled field set,
the default behavior should be to set enabled to True for the new project,
but because we are passing the wrong variable to the driver creation
method, this new project end up with the enabled field set to "nothing".

Closes-Bug: #1261976
Change-Id: I9ebfdde03c0f25cadd1323de9863a230d8058f4e

commit_message:
port test_live_block_migration into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I58f8dcbc9aeaa36e0683226f9d4837904a7d88b8

commit_message:
Object Upload validated on client side

    Perform a js validation of the Object Upload name. If the name is
not entered, the submit button will appears disabled.

Fixes bug #1125232
Change-Id: Id33f3999e9267f5fc58eb55406fc5b763597839b
Co-Authored-By: Cristian A Sanchez <cristian.a.sanchez@intel.com>

commit_message:
Add init value None to port

In file openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/instances/workflows/
create_instance.py, function handle(), add init value None to port
to avoid NameError.

Change-Id: I592207cc04efd7838c7b055d430393775ddfa313
Closes-Bug: #1264829

commit_message:
Clean up the hypervisor DataTable members columns

Refactored the class to use filters instead of passing functions.
As noted in the documentation on DataTable. Also corrected a side
effect where a template filter does not check the input value.

Change-Id: I0c4867673611228fbcffa71f65d2e9ed9a1f872e
Closes-Bug: #1203391

commit_message:
Extend options for custom flavor sorting when launching instances

Until now, flavors were sorted by RAM, ascending, by default.
An option to override this and use a custom callable instead
was introduced via the CREATE_INSTANCE_FLAVOR_SORT dict in
local_settings.py.

This patch introduces another way of using the
CREATE_INSTANCE_FLAVOR_SORT dict: by providing a flavor attribute.

Change-Id: I5b2819cc3ebc97377e673682d0b2c7ddab94e3d3
Closes-Bug: #1254524

A lot of horizon's views use the pattern:

    def get_data(self):
        if not hasattr(self, "_data"):
            # Calculate data here.
            self._data = data
        return self._data

This is copy-pasted all over the codebase. It's better to handle that
with a single decorator. In the future, we might even replace it with
some better caching approach.

with a private member, because it uses weak references to the objects,
so the cache for a given object instance will be gone as soon as that
object instance is no longer used.

commit_message:
Use memoized_method decorator in views

A lot of horizon's views use the pattern:

    def get_data(self):
        if not hasattr(self, "_data"):
            # Calculate data here.
            self._data = data
        return self._data

This is copy-pasted all over the codebase. It's better to handle that
with a single decorator. In the future, we might even replace it with
some better caching approach.

Closes-bug: #1248230
Change-Id: Id021fccf9032e5068993ec91a7774a5d0fbf29bb

commit_message:
Convert build_and_run_instance to objects

This change involved refactoring a number of test helpers so they know
whether to create stubs for an object version or a traditional version of
a test scenario. The conditional logic here will be removed when all of
the compute manager is converted to objects.

Related to blueprint icehouse-objects.
Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects.

Change-Id: If6ca114566f8abe6b9a0f164403786378809839d

commit_message:
Handle terminate_connection() exception in volume manager

Due to the fact that we sometimes need to manually terminate a volume's
connection through volume api, it's possile that these backend drivers
throw exceptions while doing that. Currently exceptions are bubbled up to
volume API not being handled. This patch logs exception in volume manager
and then raises VolumeBackendAPIException to caller.

Change-Id: If809f97998f52516af09ec21b3052b67d3a62f36
Closes-bug: #1263820

commit_message:
Tune up report and downtime intervals for l2 agent

If the neutron server erroneously thinks than the l2 agent is down
it will fail to bind a port, which can lead to VM's spawn errors.

This patch aims to add support for agent checks flags.

Change-Id: If047c5d52d10a8ca9b1b765400bdd99a29550b1e
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Steve,

At least on RHEL-style distributions, the neutron-server init script fails with no output when it can't find /etc/neutron/plugin.ini.  So, I would consider some variation of the following wording:

"If neutron-server doesn't restart successfully, make sure a symlink exists from /etc/neutron/plugin.ini to the .ini file associated with the plug-in.  For example, with the Open vSwitch plug-in:

ln -s /etc/neutron/plugins/openvswitch/ovs_neutron_plugin.ini /etc/neutron/plugin.ini"

As a long-term solution, the plug-in package should automatically create this symlink.  Perhaps we need to file a bug upstream.  Meanwhile, this wording should eliminate the immediate issue.

Matt'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2013-12-21 03:15:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Neutron expects /etc/neutron/plugin.ini

Neutron expects /etc/neutron/plugin.ini to contain the Neutron plugin
configuration, or to be a symlink to it. The guide incorrectly referred
to /etc/neutron/plugins.ini (not the s).

The typo has been corrected and the explicity ln command to create the
link added.

Change-Id: I3ac7db3ffa3215aa102cde0f1585d7d0756c0fb2
Closes-Bug: #1260173
backport: havana

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-20 07:16:48.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up routes on FIP disassoc in Midonet plugin

The update of the floatingip_db was happening before the disassociation, so the
disassociation happened on new data. The old data was required to identify the
router_id. This fix changes the order of the disassociation and the
floatingip_db update. This fix has the side affect of fixing the tempest test
"test_floating_ips" in the midonet plugin.

Closes-bug: #1262122

Change-Id: I8c855cd53bd18a0987f9cfc66c3741eccca7031d
'}]
commit_message:
Clean up routes on FIP disassoc in Midonet plugin

The update of the floatingip_db was happening before the disassociation, so the
disassociation happened on new data. The old data was required to identify the
router_id. This fix changes the order of the disassociation and the
floatingip_db update. This fix has the side affect of fixing the tempest test
"test_floating_ips" in the midonet plugin.

Closes-bug: #1262122

Change-Id: I8c855cd53bd18a0987f9cfc66c3741eccca7031d

commit_message:
Add eclipse project files to .gitignore

Like some of the other projects (nova, heat, oslo, glance, cinder)
git ignore eclipse project files. This will remove manual steps
for people developing from eclipse.

commit_message:
Add demo app for Mistral

 * Simple server
 * expose one endpoint - /tasks
 * recieve correct signal from mistral
  about task execution, log 'task N started,
 task N finished'
 * logging

Change-Id: I230eac12319be820d64612d242b9190a10be946e

ZhiQiang, these are minor comments about commit message format, so I can vote you with +1,  and please take care of these commit message next time, thanks for your patch.'}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2013-12-26 03:27:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Haomeng,Wang

The first opinion about short description is right, but considering this change is too simple to add description, I decide not to do it. However, what I type in review already more than that desc... :)

The second opinion is not acceptable, I found that ironic doesn't have its own HACKING file, which means it will follow rules defined in openstack/hacking/doc/index.rst, but I don't find rule about the order of change-id.

If we really want to force some rules about commit message format, we can write our own HACKING, or maybe commit to openstack/hacking too, then every contributor will know how to and why they should avoid some specific behavior.

And if we do so, a hacking rule can be added, so pep8 will check format automatically as how it does now.

Technically, each time I commit a patch, I put bug id in the end of commit message, and don't care which line the git-gerrit will insert the change-id to. commit_message:
Add API schema for v3 fixed_ips.

This patch adds the API schema for v3 fixed_ips API.

This schema restricts values of reserve/unreserve to None, because the
values are not used and the existing unittests pass None as the values.

This patch also fixes v3 fixed_ips unittests because WSGI passes **kwargs
like {'body': {u'reserve': u'None'}, 'id': '192.168.1.1'} to action() of
fixed_ips but the unittests did not do it.

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-validation-fw

Change-Id: Idce8c1ac198ed502a6ef6a9b482ceaa504d9bf01

commit_message:
Move redirect handling to session

Particularly 305 is expected to be handled by the tests so we need to
handle this centrally if we want to have session and non-session clients
to work the same way.

Change-Id: Id4ec35ddd8b8304d24df9e6cd2ab995d123ef125

TypeError on Python 3.3. See:

This helps fix some tests on Python3.3.

'}]
commit_message:
HTTPretty: update to 0.7.1

The 0.7.1 release has a fix for the parse_querystring function, which raised a
TypeError on Python 3.3. See:

https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/HTTPretty/commit/5c6e77615f4083b9daf4a0148349f3185dcaff05

This helps fix some tests on Python3.3.

Change-Id: I8f28c5dfdcb25b2c131a4b8866547025064caac6

commit_message:
Don't install pre-release software with tox

Override the tox pip install command to avoid using the
"--pre" option which is the default in tox.  "--pre" means "Include
pre-release and development versions."  By default, pip will only
install stable versions of software, and that is the behavior we want.

Change-Id: Ida5e440d1bdb9f8e9031277ea53a02d2ef171438
Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>

commit_message:
Brick connector revised fix for NFS drivers

This change fixes the error that comes
while getting brick connector and attaching volumes
in case of NFS drivers in cinder. The attribute for
mount point base was not passed to attach_volume method
as the connector initialization logic is common for all
types of protocols. It is fixed by populating
the required parameter in the RemoteFsConnector
by extracting it from connection properties. The infrastructure
for fixing this situation for remote fs drivers is implemented
in this fix. The drivers need to override the method
_get_mount_point_base in their implementation. NFS driver
implements it. GlusterFs implementation of the method to follow
in a separate patch. Hence marking it partial fix.

Change-Id: Id61a437fca1870529fa8b85f7fc2f73eae665294
Partial-Bug: #1238085
(cherry picked from commit 1cd362630655798e5ff4c058b3f44862ae61c801)

I verified that it looks good : https://gist.github.com/dachary/7500777 and that it matches the blueprint at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet-openstack/ceph-blueprint#I_want_to_try_this_module.2C_heard_of_ceph.2C_want_to_see_it_in_action'}, {'account_id': 2064, 'date': '2013-11-16 16:22:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

@David Moreau Simard : these are not instructions, this is a user story. It is not something you would refer to as a manual or as a repository of example. It is something you look at the first time you run into the module. If your story is very close to one of the story that is listed in the README, you know that the module has been designed for you. It does not necessarily mean that it will be a perfect match. Conversively, if you do *not* find a user story that matches your use case, it is a sign that the puppet module is probably not what you want to use.'}, {'account_id': 9061, 'date': '2013-11-18 15:30:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Okay, I see where you're going.
I'm going to need convincing, though as I don't feel it is relevant to put user stories in the readme.

I browsed a few dozen modules and none of them had stories.

The readme should be kept as concise as possible with information about what it does, instructions relative to usage and development, limitations and such.

This would be something that would be at home in a larger documentation, maybe in the wiki."}, {'account_id': 2064, 'date': '2013-11-18 23:14:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

When it comes to puppet modules the README is all the documention one usually expects. And all useful README include at least one example, which is a degraded form of user story ( because it usually do state the need the example is supposed to satisfy ). 

I wish *all* puppet modules out there had user stories. That would save everyone a huge amount of time because more often than not you end up realizing after trying the module for yourself that it was not designed for you. Which would be quite obvious if you had a few user stories to read.

In the case of puppet-ceph the user stories must be prominently facing the user because we want to make it clear that we spent a lot of time ( and we did ;-) trying to address a large spectrum of user stories'}, {'account_id': 9061, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:55:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

I gave myself some time to think about this and I'm sorry to say that I'm maintaining my position. While I believe use case documentation is necessary, I feel they do not belong in the README.

In time, my opinion is that they will make the README too heavy.
We should try to keep the README as concise and short as possible while maintaining what is essential to get started.

I'd be willing to commit to a compromise with perhaps a link in the readme that leads back to a wiki page where the use cases are documented.

I'm not -2'ing this because I'll let the community decide wether or not this goes through."}, {'account_id': 2064, 'date': '2013-11-25 19:46:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@ahmad : for the sake of consensus and getting this out of the way, could you please move the use case to a USECASES.md file that is linked from the README.md file ?"}, {'account_id': 9324, 'date': '2013-11-26 07:28:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 9324, 'date': '2013-11-26 07:31:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-26 09:19:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Works for me

commit_message:
Adds use case to USECASES.md

It is a use case listed in https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet-
openstack/ceph-blueprint and it would be a useful example when
considering what the puppet-ceph module can do. It must be linked
from the README.md

Closes-Bug: #1243331
Change-Id: I6d477353a0e1bc00eef77e96099e92845f47f21f

[{'created': '2013-11-27 10:19:32.000000000', 'message': "Remove middleware ratelimits from v3 api

The ratelimit middleware isn't really useful. That is pointed out
by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34821/. And it didn't get any
object from mail-list:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-November/020291.html

This patch remove ratelimit middleware and limits extension. The config option
'api_rate_limit' is only valid in v2 api. The pipeline factory for v3 api won't
check that option anymore. For compatibility, if user is still using old
'api-paste.init', pipeline factory will ignore to load ratelimit middleware, and
print warning message to user for notice ratelimit is deprecated in v3 api.

Closes-bug: 1255471
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ifeae0504e11089f95e4d8af58bcb7372dca87f81

commit_message:
Remove middleware ratelimits from v3 api

The ratelimit middleware isn't really useful. That is pointed out
by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34821/. And it didn't get any
object from mail-list:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-November/020291.html

This patch remove ratelimit middleware and limits extension. The config option
'api_rate_limit' is only valid in v2 api. The pipeline factory for v3 api won't
check that option anymore. For compatibility, if user is still using old
'api-paste.init', pipeline factory will ignore to load ratelimit middleware, and
print warning message to user for notice ratelimit is deprecated in v3 api.

Closes-bug: 1255471
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ifeae0504e11089f95e4d8af58bcb7372dca87f81

commit_message:
Fix invalid port range in security group rule create

An earlier commit introduced a change that creates security groups. In
the rules for tcp and udp, ports 1-65536 are allowed. This is
incorrect, it should be 1-65535.

This patch corrects this error.

Closes-Bug: #1264635
Change-Id: I83a7471ebf6d3d3bfeff6b16a051880d876370b1

commit_message:
Add Service Catalog definition to identity-api

The service catalog layout is depended upon by multiple services but was
never formally defined. Add the service catalog layout at a full token
example.

Change-Id: I43bb18fa5e33be4612cabe7517b5690d4c42b7e4

commit_message:
Use uuid instead of uuidutils

Each project should directly use the standard uuid module.
uuidutils will be deprecated/removed in this cycle.

This patch replaces every uuidutils.generate_uuid() with
str(uuid.uuid4()) and uuidutils.is_uuid_like()
with utils.is_uuid_like().

Change-Id: I43642d4f1e137c14134b3d544e367b504b9851ac
Closes-Bug: #1253497

'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-12-18 09:37:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

(3 inline comments)

Hi Doug,

This patch fix your problem I can understand well.
However, please have a look at my comments and let's see you we could do it better.

A lot of changes are in progress regarding to security groups and in my opinion, we should:

1) Ensure security groups are working when using ML2 plugin with heterogeneous drivers (Linux Bridge + OVS), since they use different firewall_driver values.
2) Update puppet-neutron taking in consideration Nachi's patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/21946/ - a lot of changes have been done to fix neutron bugs.

For 1), I would like to see a bug report and for 2) I'm going to create a blueprint.

I don't like to be that guy by -2 a patch but while we are not sure, I prefer avoid accidental merging.

Thank you to bringing that, please ping me on IRC if you want to discuss about it.

Emilien (EmilienM on freenode)"}, {'account_id': 9415, 'date': '2013-12-18 22:14:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Abandoned

Hi Emilien,

I understand completely.  This was a quick fix on my part to get around something that looked mostly/completely non-functional (at least in my environment).

You've got great suggestions.  I think it makes sense to abandon this change pending further testing and your blueprint.

Doug"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-12-19 10:02:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It's kind of weird to abandon this patch, since I'm quite sure you face a bug that someone will hit also.

Could you at least file a bug in the launchpad in explaining your environment and explaining how do you configure neutron ?

It will help us to fix the problem if it comes from puppet-neutron module.

Thank you,

Emilien"}, {'account_id': 9415, 'date': '2013-12-19 14:05:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Restored

Undoing abandon.  Bug 1262678 has been created.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-19 14:07:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Adding ml2 firewall_driver parameter

When using the ml2 core plugin, the firewall_driver parameter
must be set to enable the neutron security-group extension/API.

commit_message:
Replaces location to be backed up during prepare

Reasons:
- prepare method preserves data always from CONF.mount_point.
- CONF.mount_point could be changed by user to point to
  mount_point name where user wants data disk to be mounted.
- /var/lib/mysql is the location, where data would exist always
  prior to prepare method being called following package installation.

Changes:
- Replaced CONF.mount_point by default_data_dir as the
  location to be backed up during prepare call.

Change-Id: I7efcbe1bafcbc961d4e20ddaa55efaa086a0cdc5
Closes-Bug: #1261354

commit_message:
fix bug(1246551):del immediately after reboot vm

If the instance was booted again before instance file
deleted, such as rebooted and destroyed at the same time,
if restart has been completed but destroy is still delete
instance file, this may be cause vm is still running but
instance file has been deleted.

Change-Id: If6db10c34f05bd335cb306dc2dcb0379056c882d
Closes-Bug: #1246551

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-17 09:35:35.000000000', 'message': 'Change ceilometer sql pool size

Because when we are running a all-in-one installation in devstack,
and ceilometer share the database with other compomnents.

To make sure that ceilometer have the time to consume all the
notifications that come from every componements during a tempest run.
We must change the default pool size to ensure it can open enough
database connection to write all the received notifications in it.

Fixes bug #1243251

Change-Id: I953d16d71a356bd7606f1b1640e7991b418c3286
'}]
commit_message:
Change ceilometer sql pool size

Because when we are running a all-in-one installation in devstack,
and ceilometer share the database with other compomnents.

To make sure that ceilometer have the time to consume all the
notifications that come from every componements during a tempest run.
We must change the default pool size to ensure it can open enough
database connection to write all the received notifications in it.

Fixes bug #1243251

Change-Id: I953d16d71a356bd7606f1b1640e7991b418c3286

commit_message:
Consolidate under and overcloud passwd scripts

We have nearly identical setup passwords scripts for both over and
under clouds. Consolidating into one setup-passwords script that
takes a -c option and defaults to setting up UNDERCLOUD passwords.

Change-Id: I0479813585635c5d13467231c6e60e0a8ec1c683

commit_message:
Makes CONF.mount_point editable for deployment

Reasons:

1. If we change the value of CONF.mount_point it does not works,
because of too many wrong paths and hard-codings.
2. MYSQL_BASE_DIR is hard-coded as "/var/lib/mysql" and
over that has only 1 legitimate usage, when wiping logfiles.
3. No provision for updation of config_contents/my.cnf
if CONF.mount_point has a different value.
4. Initial data-files location to be backed up has been written
as CONF.mount_point which is no good when having different
value for CONF.mount_point.

Changes:
1. Initial data-file location updated as "/var/lib/mysql",
because thats where mysql creates its first datafiles; Logic is
if the location exists back it up.
2. Added code to update datadir in config_contents and my.cnf
when using a value other than "/var/lib/mysql" in CONF.mount_point.
3. Replaced MYSQL_BASE_DIR in wipe_ib_logfiles with CONF.mount_point,
because that is the place where we would have the log_files.

Change-Id: I58111ae9ef949be910a21967350b0ac613cb97e7
Closes-Bug: #1243874

commit_message:
The syntax in spec file need backward compatible with ruby 1.8

Ruby 1.8 does not support this syntax 'user: "ceilometer"' in the params
of function, since the RHEL6.4 is still using this ruby version, we need
fix it to keep the backward compatibility.

Closes-bug: #1262965

Change-Id: I94317c1632283d3b4742cda1c5fd719b7b199297

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-12-11 13:07:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

hi Stuart, I'll update the commit message with my next patchset but please not that this is intended to prevent updates to all users, as you noticed, not just to admins.

On the reasons, there has been some quick conversation on IRC but it is certainly good to wrap up it here:

the basic idea is that updates to an image size and checksum shouldn't happen after the image data becomes available, neither of the two is subject to change especially considering image data immutable; v2 api makes size and checksum readonly attributes so with this change v1 will basically behave as v2

we also reject images at the time of uploading if the size posted in the request does not match the real image size, so this change just builds up on your previous changes preventing all users from modifying that"}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-12-11 15:09:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-11 16:11:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Doesn't seem to work

While we're picking nits, should the subject be more something like "Prevent admin users from changing size and checksum in v1". For me that better describes the change in behaviour.

I wrote the original patch to restrict size changes to admin users only. I was thinking of fsck type operations which an admin or script may want to perform.

commit_message:
Prevent admin users from changing size and checksum in v1 api

This patch changes the v1 api behaviour so that it will refuse
updates to size and checksum for images in 'active' or 'saving'
states. This will make v1 api behaving consistently with v2 api
which already considers size and checksum readonly.

Change-Id: I198144c7ad94f2dbcd41b069718fa9e8b92e47ea
Closes-Bug: 1220797

commit_message:
Add devtest real BM MAC and PM command support

Add top level support for using real hardware with devtest.
This patch adds the ability to set MACS, PM_IPS, PM_USERS,
and PM_PASSWORDS to devtest.sh which is then used when
calling setup-baremetal.

If these variables are set there is no need to call create-nodes
for virtualized undercloud/overcloud machines so when MACS
is set those are selectively disabled.

The motivation with this commit is to reach parity with current
tripleo-ci features and eventually restructure tripleo-ci to
make use of the devtest scripts.

Change-Id: I41847e89c6b0c250c759f33182113af92e8a3c98

Added profiler library

This library will be used to gather openstack performance stats.

Related to blueprint profiling

Added profiler library usage sample

Synced profiler code from oslo.
This library will be used to gather openstack performance stats.

Related to blueprint profiling

commit_message:
Cleaned up version.xsd documentation

There was a typo, it should be the

compliant was mispelled as "complient"

another type "my" was changed to may

DEPRECATED - corrected back

added a transition word "of" before enumeration
Removed extra "and"

Change-Id: I414242a14712259846f8dde9ebf51fa8b04efecc

A common pattern in template authoring is to use a
AWS::AutoScaling::LaunchConfiguration as a simple container
for metadata that is only available after server boot.

When servers poll for this metadata, the AccessKey, User and AccessPolicy
resources determine whether the keypair has access to the resource
the metadata is requested for.

valid json which the test asserts the exact content of.

commit_message:
ServerCfnInitTestJSON also tests metadata polling

A common pattern in template authoring is to use a
AWS::AutoScaling::LaunchConfiguration as a simple container
for metadata that is only available after server boot.

When servers poll for this metadata, the AccessKey, User and AccessPolicy
resources determine whether the keypair has access to the resource
the metadata is requested for.

This test polls for the launch config metadata using cfn-get-metadata.
By the time user_data has finished executing, /tmp/smoke-status contains
valid json which the test asserts the exact content of.

Change-Id: Ibdb7c42f021a2c62526be5bfd45f070586c949f5

'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-12-18 15:17:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I am not (yet) convinced that we should switch the order in which the delete_*_precommit and delete_*_postcommit (or delete_*_db and delete_*_device) methods are called on the drivers. All the precommit and postcommit methods are named the way they are, and are called in the order they are, based on the idea that the DB's state is authoritative, and the mechanism's external (non-DB) state is being brought into sync with the DB's state after the DB transaction has been committed. I just don't see anything different about delete operations that requires that the mechanisms' external state be updated before the DB transaction has been committed. Am I missing something here? I could easily have missed a key point buried in the discussion.

It seems to me that there are really three interrelated aspects of the driver API that we should consider improving:

1) The Context objects should provide the drivers with the previous and current values of all relevant state in both the precommit and postcommmit methods. This is done right now for the attribute dictionary, but not for the segments or for the binding. This would seem straightforward to implement and should not break existing drivers.

2) The binding-related operations may need some modification. Right now, bind_port, unbind_port, and validate_port_binding are all called inside DB transactions. This prevents drivers from interacting with external controllers or devices. The binding and unbinding processes probably should occur outside of a DB transaction. This may require a state machine in the DB so that only a single process attempts to bind a particular port at a time. We also should make sure that update_port_precommit and update_port_postcommit are always called on all the drivers when the port's binding state changes. If we do unbind the port as a 1st step in deleting it, all registered mechanism drivers should see a port_update_precommit followed by a port_update_postcommit followed by a port_delete_precommit and finally a port_delete_postcommit. Its not totally clear to me yet whether unbind_port should be called on the bound mechanism driver before or after port_update_precommit is called on all the registered drivers, but I'm leaning towards after.

3) Since mechanisms' external state is always updated after the DB state change has been committed, its possible the DB and external state might get out of sync. This could happen if a server dies between committing the transaction and calling the driver's postcommit method. It could also happen if postcommit methods for different transactions on the same resource are executed concurrently in different threads or different processes, and calls to the driver end up being made in a different order than the transactions were committed. One approach to solving this might be to use a state machine to hold off new updates to a resource until all drivers' postcommit methods have successfully been called for the previous update. Another approach might be for a background task to periodically sweep through all the resources in the DB and call the drivers' to let them check that the external state is consistent.

So it seems the most fundamental questions here are about the relationship between the DB state and drivers' external state. Is the DB state authoritative? Is lazily syncing the external state, hopefully with eventual consistency, sufficient? Or does the external state need to be more tightly synchronized with the DB state, making it effectively participate in the transactions?"}, {'account_id': 6558, 'date': '2013-12-18 17:50:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Bob, 
I this is what I wrote in the email, posting it here for general discussion. This is really in reference to your point number 3: 

Sukhdev


Bob, 

You articulated it very well. We should treat DB as "true source". If we build our framework and design around that principal, we are golden. 
With such a principal in mind, once a transaction is committed to DB, it becomes a true source and the drivers should synchronize to that - there is no need to have tight coupling. 

The only inconsistency I noticed/observed is that ML2 framework seems to behave differently for creates and deletes. For instance, for a create operation, if the transaction is committed to DB, and later some driver fails, the framework actively participates and deletes the transaction from the DB, whereas it does not exhibit the same behavior for delete. Put it other way, if create operation goes out of sync, ML2 framework fixes it, but when a delete operation goes out of sync, it leaves on the driver to fix it. 

It is not necessarily wrong, but, inconsistent.  If we had a simple create/delete operations to DB (not pre/post), and let the drivers treat them a true source and act on the state change in DB, that would not create such inconsistency...'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-12-19 18:54:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Sukhdev,

Good point regarding the inconsistent error handling/recovery between create and update/delete. Undoing the partial create is easy, but I'm not sure automatically undoing a partial update or delete is realistic. This probably should be discussed via a separate bug, patch review and/or email thread.

Does this inconsistent error handling relate to the question of whether the precommit/postcommit methods should be reversed (and renamed) for deletes? If so, how? If not, are we getting to a consensus on whether or not to reverse the order for deletes?

-Bob"}, {'account_id': 5217, 'date': '2013-12-20 18:56:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think instead of providing custom sync service in the plugin, it might be better to fix the db transaction model in the ML2 plugin. I see some places in the ML2 plugin which need some changes to fix that behavior.

There can be unforeseen issues with plugin provided sync service which may simply focus on sync of the hardware. There may be events like giving out dhcp address to a vm which may have failed which may be hard to sync at a later time.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 6694, 'date': '2013-12-20 22:41:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Bob -
If update_port() is called on the port unbinding event and a port_context.bound_segment and port_context.original_bound_segment contains the appropriate information then this would work for the cisco_nexus driver.
Not sure if you already have ideas on how this would be implemented and/or have looked at Mathieu's first take on fixing this issue
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/62380/1."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-28 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

commit_message:
Calls in delete methods should be in reverse order as create

*** PROPOSAL ONLY REVIEW. ***

The methods called from the delete methods in ml2/plugin.py should
be made in the reverse order in which they appear in the respective
create methods.

*** Add bug# here. ***

Change-Id: Ia746dee85faa3e74b21a53d1c37c8dea15efbc25

commit_message:
The syntax in spec file need backward compatible with ruby 1.8

Ruby 1.8 does not support this syntax 'user: "keystone"' in the params
of function, since the RHEL6.4 is still using this ruby version, we need
fix it to keep the backward compatibility.

Closes-bug: #1262965

Change-Id: Ibf479fc1fd42609156f1b6b9cd5aa24c2ba552ad

Some suggestions to avoid repeated code.'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-12-21 05:18:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi Justin,

I can't seem to find a convincing case anywhere that these notifications *must* be dictionaries. The wiki that is linked by this bug confusingly states identifies the payload field as "payload - A python dictionary of attributes. Note that the payload can contain any python data type, and varies by the entry in the event_type field." I'm concerned that changing what is produced will break existing notification consumers.

Can you help me understand why this is needed and why we can expect that it won't cause undue hardship for downstream notifications consumers?

Also, FWIW I think koofoss' suggestions makes sense.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-28 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Abandoned

commit_message:
Correct URL in v1 test_get_images_unauthorized

The test code in
unit/v1/test_api.py:TestGlanceAPI.test_get_images_unauthorized
requests for the wrong URL - instead of requesting for "/images" it
requests for "/images/detail" (making it identical to the
test_get_images_unauthorized test).

Change-Id: I308e73966bcbb27287012d7b5dcdcc9d2a9f2e18
Closes-Bug: #1264428

commit_message:
Fix missed management_url setter in v3 client

Setting management_url is intended to mean that this is an overriding
URL not one received from the service catalog. This was fixed for
project scoped tokens but was missed from domain scoped tokens.

Change-Id: I8484f4a26a5695ef7ae962918ad442fe20bd2caa
Related Change: I2fa41e2ae1b853bbb254698cf94b9314eb0f0903
Related-Bug: #1252927

subject: Add service catalog to domain scoped token fixture

commit_message:
Add service catalog to domain scoped token fixture

This was simply forgotten previously and testing that required a service
catalog was done with the project token. This has led to some problems
of not testing the domain paths correctly.

Fix the one test that was incorrectly relying on an empty service
catalog being returned from a domain scoped token.

Change-Id: I66e3a9302d6a73ba17d4ed45f2366d9bb91461ab

commit_message:
Added step to change 'libvirt_type' when running compute on VM

Quite a few people initially try OpenStack by running each node on
a virtual machine. In some cases, either the hypervisor and/or CPU
lack support for hardware acceleration required by KVM on the compute
node. I added a step including how to test for hardware acceleration
support within the virtual machine and change 'libvirt_type' from KVM
to QEMU if the test fails.

Change-Id: I519cdff8c2c1b6a8d1d2b9d5181b205362651b85
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1264175

commit_message:
Add oauthlib library to replace oauth2

The current oauth library (oauth2) is unmainted and has security
issues, as mentioned in:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1240382

The better choice would be to use oauthlib.

This patch is to add oauthlib. When we fully remove oauth2 from
keystone, we can remove oauth2 from requirements.

Change-Id: I1c14c71fb37d8e164585d785c7755eccb4c9c51e

commit_message:
port test_aggregates and test_hosts into nova v3 part2

this port test_aggregates and test_hosts into nova v3,
and port the corresponding client aggregate_client and
host_client.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I0f7b4f548f68b634258bb396bd3d245b02561e3a

commit_message:
port test_aggregates and test_hosts into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Idef3e36468ff2e7b7bd0517fdfa86e0b6c209e72

commit_message:
Common ConnectionRefused class

Reason:
- Almost all projects using their own custom classes for exception
  which occures when API service refuses connection, or re-raises exception from httplib/requests.
Changes:
- Adding class ConnectionRefused, inherited from ClientException

Change-Id: I96385a50168dea17189149e9353ecaced6e15ab7

commit_message:
Fix the obsolete exception message

The exception message is outdated and misleading. This particular error
has nothing to do with Essex release, but rather means that the DB
schema is not under version control, but has tables nevertheless.

Change-Id: I5254a51ba86eb6ae2a9adc4295cf921fb5051f81

commit_message:
Fixed issue with undeleted instances

* Now savanna delete assigned floating ip by its id both for neutron and nova network
* Also now savanna behaves in this way: due to unexpected error in floating ip deletion savanna removes instance anyway
* Added unit-tests

Change-Id: I5d7d1e8db22f1dd2057b7ba64e02834d36d3497b
Closes-Bug: #1262783

 * new exceptions - Mistral, DBDuplicateEntry

commit_message:
Fix misused assertTrue in unit tests

The patch merged under review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/61816/3
still uses assertTrue instead of assertEqual.

This patch properly corrects this.

Change-Id: I09fd4b7355dd721b513febd0669cb1368b5cda19
Closes-Bug: #1226374

The "select all" checkbox in tables didn't work due to a missing CSS class.
Add the missing class so that the checkbox behaves as expected.

Change-Id: I5dcfdf9a7a60ea516c5343fabeb7a8f79b107fe7
Closes-Bug: #1259537

commit_message:
Fix behavior of select all checkbox

The "select all" checkbox in tables didn't work due to a missing CSS class.
Add the missing class so that the checkbox behaves as expected.

Change-Id: I5dcfdf9a7a60ea516c5343fabeb7a8f79b107fe7
Closes-Bug: #1259537

commit_message:
Removal of underscorejs library

    Underscore is poorly used into Horizon. All underscore functions
have been rewritten with jQuery utils, this will reduce the
fragmentation of Horizon code, and lower the javascript footprint.

Change-Id: Ica1469e115d9e135d5a3a0795b4b5e1809f4d6b4
Implements: blueprint delete-underscore

Use HTTPClient from common Oslo code

In the process of unification of the clients code we should
reuse common functionality from Oslo.

bp common-client-library-2

commit_message:
Refactor network client: add create_ and update_ methods

Automatic create_ and update_ methods are added.
create_pool and update_pool modified in this patch serve
as an example of the usage.
For XML client simplistic json to xml serialization is used for now.

Change-Id: I8eb17d2aacfd4d2eacd8821b4b66e112626843a7

this converts min_count and max_count to type:int in nova
v3 api.
If the string type hasn't been converted, in the method
_check_num_instances_quota of nova/compute/api.py, something
like req_ram = '2'*128 will occur. That's why the issue in

"}]
commit_message:
convert min_count and max_count to type int in nova v3 api

this converts min_count and max_count to type:int in nova
v3 api.
If the string type hasn't been converted, in the method
_check_num_instances_quota of nova/compute/api.py, something
like req_ram = '2'*128 will occur. That's why the issue in
bug 1254616 arise.

Change-Id: I567b249e7a30681980ed760d5d09aad4c8e603b9
Closes-bug: 1254616

commit_message:
Fix incorrect exit status checking in sshutils

Method channel.is_closed() was called for checknig ssh command is
finished, but in some cases command was finished, but channel was
still open. Method exit_status_ready() should be called instead.

Also removed unnecessary call of fileno() and shutdown_write(), and
use select instead of poll.

Closes-Bug: #1263645

Change-Id: I9484fca758370b68553e98e9d4c409b493df1117

commit_message:
Fix AutoScalingTest test suite error

Fix the credential return value tuple order of Orchestration-
ScenarioTest to match that of its parent class, OfficialClientTest.

Change-Id: Ie60403f17e23cb4843578bd389ae3e0c8b22e4b2
Closes-Bug: #1263220

and server provider modules without _engine.py and _provider.py suffixes" or

commit_message:
Preserve consistency in module namings

We rename several modules in the system (mostly in unit tests) so that their
namings become consistent throughout the code.

"Consistency" means here following certain rules like "name all deploy engine
and server provider modules without _engine.py and _provider.py suffixes" or
"name all unit tests like test_<tested_module>.py".

We also add a couple of new folders in unit tests so that the unit tests
structure strictly resembles that of tested modules.

Blueprint unit-tests-refactoring

Change-Id: Ia7b6afce0d1e20b969b56301e0c9ad0f94cc60e4

commit_message:
Fix SignalResponder signature response when deleted

The test_FnGetAtt_delete_not_found test previously did nothing
because the rsrc.delete() was just getting a generator function
and not actually doing the delete.  This uncovered that we'd throw
an error trying to get the AlarmUrl after resource deletion, so
ensure we return None when the credentials have been deleted.

Change-Id: I7edbaeae26a53e8e424195d2b389b7d45b414da5

commit_message:
Reset CONF for topology_helper and services during unit tests

This commit addresses an intermittent unit test failure by ensuring
that the CONF is reset to its original value after execution of
unit tests that alter it.

Fixes: bug #1263931

Change-Id: I2970f10f677507f413bfe87338fb3e301b9699a4

commit_message:
Fix for additional statuses for test processing

Now 'skipped' test status is processing in StoragePlugin by type
comparison with nose.plugins.skip.SkipTest class. This should work both in
python 2.6 and 2.7.

Change-Id: I20be3784f2d5c6cda4575d7e9a36ab6ec278e795

commit_message:
API: Validate driver when creating/updating a node

When creating or updating a node, the API will check whether the driver
supplied is active or not.

Change-Id: I6cf9dcb0b81cf9dfa02869993c4bbc3e9cbd92a0

commit_message:
heat engine should log error message when WaitCondition failed

When WaitCondition failed, then heat stack will go to CREATE_FAILED
state. For such case, heat engine should log error message but not
info message.

Change-Id: Ibe3d48ed934ed6633a7ccd44cec95895250b9a2e
Closes-Bug: #1258993

This is fine. The only thing that is missing is a description of the rules for how a globally unique name is constructed with different combinations of the optional id components. Are all optional combinations allowed are only a subset of them? If an optional component is missing how does this effect the dotted notation for the global name?'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-13 18:43:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Remove the service ids.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-13 18:43:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Do not merge

'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2013-12-13 19:51:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I would like to know more what is wrong with service_id name-space component.A particular deployment can build up name-space without it, so it is not enforced.

As a service provider our roles are name-spaced with service and our use case will not be solved without service id component in name-space component.'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2013-12-13 20:10:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

David, I will add some rule in the spec.

How about, containment hierarchy drives the name space direction?
e.g. domain contains and  projects owns services. in that case 

domain_id.project_id.service_id.role_name

In the absence of these optional components role_name it self has to be unique. Dots are just a separator and will not present in this case.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-12-14 12:17:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think it would be clearer to administrators if specific examples of each variant are given (as in the original etherpad on this topic) i.e.
the overall structure is domain_id.project_id.service_id.role_name
where an optional component is missing then the following structures are used:
id...role_name is a domain named role
.id..role_name is a project named role in the default domain
id1..id2.role_name is a service named role in domain id1
regards
david'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2013-12-16 21:31:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-16 21:41:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

- gate-noop http://logs.openstack.org/97/61897/4/check/gate-noop/5c4ee61 : SUCCESS in 3s

'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2013-12-18 16:46:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(4 inline comments)

A couple of opinions and formatting issues.

At first glance this doesn't really seem like an extension at all. It looks like you plan on changing the existing role apis? All the endpoints in this api are existing endpoints, and I could feasibly just append your api specs to the exisitng roles api and make the attributes optional. Which would be the same effect?

If you plan on keeping it an extension, it should have it's own routers/controller/backend to preserve the roles existing state."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-12-18 17:06:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Do not merge

"serviceIDs have no business in a role defintion" -ayoung

I generally agree. This would be a good candidate for an out of tree API & implementation to serve the need, which seem to be proprietary in nature anyway.

Marked corresponding BP as obsolete.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-18 17:10:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The -2 is going to stay as long as the API spec includes superfluos fields on the Role Definition.

Service IDs in particular make no sense to have on a role.  To Say that a role *defintion* is tied to a specific service refelcts a fundamental misunderstanding of what a role is.  A role is nothing more than a string used to collect up permissions so that they do not have to be independently defined.  If you wish to Apply that role to a specific service, that is fine, and there are mechanisms to do that, but nothing should prevent that same role from being applied to other services.

Two potential other scopes worth thinking about:  apply this role to a subset of servcies, or apply this role to this set of 3 sercices.  Neither of those would be supported by tying it to the service ID.     In fact, there is no abstraction that collects things that way.

And it doesn't matter. What is going to apply the role is the policy file associated with the endpoint.  So if a Glance endpoint wants to apply a role names "keystone/admin" to an API, it is allowed to do so.  And note that the name needs to be unambiguous.  We are not doing LDAP style names like service=keystone,role=admin" in the policy rules.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-12-18 21:44:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Adam
I am rather surprised by your comment, because on 4 Dec when we were discussing the design of role naming, we had the following email exchange in which you said the design was very clean and would work. It seems like the only difference between the current design and the one of 4 Dec is replacing slash / separator with fullstop . separator (or am I missing something?) FYI the email of 4 Dec said

On 12/04/2013 12:40 PM, David Chadwick wrote:
> Hi Adam
>
> I understand your problem: having projects and services which have the
> same name, then the lineage of a role containing this name is not
> deterministically known without some other rule or syntax that can
> differentiate between the two.
>
> Since domains contain projects which contain services then isnt the
> containment hierarchy already known and predetermined? If it is then:
>
> 4 name components mean it is a service specified role
> 3 name components mean it is a project specified role
> 2 name components mean it is a domain specified role
> 1 name component means it is globally named role (from the default domain)
>
> a null string means the default domain or all projects in a domain. You
> would never have null for a service name.
>
> admin means the global admin role
> /admin ditto
> x/admin means the admin of the X domain
> x/y/admin means the admin role for the y project in domain x
> //x/admin means admin for service x from the default domain
> etc.
>
> will that work?
Very clean.  Yes. That will work.'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2013-12-19 17:19:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks Steve Martinelli, It would be easy to answer yous questions but first community members has to understand why it is needed otherwise I will keep answering the question and keep getting *The -2 is going to stay as long....* responses. 

It seems community members are not even want to understand the real concerns which comes in distributed architectural setup and  proposing *ambiguous* workaround without knowing potential challenges in a particular deployment model.

Dolph, "Marked corresponding BP as obsolete" is not acceptable, as it is "the" most important requirement for us without this we can not utilize Keystone with full scale in our deployment.

At the same time I want to keep this BP alive, as I would like to setup a meeting for this BP in future design summit along with bigger audience so that, I can explain the need to other OpenStack service communities and also get sometime from our busiest members. 

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-19 17:35:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Arvind,

You are trying to solve a problem than no one else has expressed.  As such, the need to do so is suspect, but I give you the benefit of the doubt to be ahead of the crowd here, and so I've been entertaining it.

However, what you are proposing has ramifications far beyond the BP that you are proposing:  it would require changing how policy is enforced, and you have not provided either mechanism for distributing that additional data.

It still seems to me that you do not understand the current model, not have you attmepted to fix the current model to your use cases.  Yes, I have read and understand your documents, I think you are mistaken in the need for having different "types" of namespaces.  You are taking the traditional object oriented approach where everything is inheritance, and I am telling you that, in this case, favor composition over inheritance, and you get a better, more flexible system.

And we have had this conversation repeatedly for the last two months.'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2013-12-19 18:25:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Adam,

Yes, no one expressed this because we are the only one in the community with specific deployment model and that is why it is hard for them to make sense out of it.

I have stared a etherpad to discuss the ramifications, so that I can make everyone happy but seems you did not explains the ramifications over there but some agreement (refer your email on 12/04/2013). With the help of David, we came up with generic design which can accommodate all current (not future and unrealistic) possible use case and I don't see any ramifications except the Keystone, which OK.

I don't want to go more bookish here as it need more practical thinking than conceptual thinking. 

I think we should stop here unless you are really willing to solve a problem and some spare time to spend, I can start the etherpad again. I would appreciate if you come up with one detailed solution for problems listed in BP and ramifications with my proposal which impact out of Keystone scope. Otherwise it will be waste of time again. 

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-27 06:03:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
API spec for OS-NS-ROLES extension

This extension allows role creator to optionally link roles with
a name-space to avoid name collision and to make role names globally
unique.
Optionally, this extension will allow role creators to associate
roles with resource for which the role is valid.

Change-Id: Icf9322c1d67c6acb66a338e5bc72e44bd552bd7a
Implements: blueprint name-spaced-roles

"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-12-06 00:04:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

The nova commit in the commit message isn't working for me. Could you link to some blueprints that talk about the origin of this code and why an existing library like colander couldn't be used (even if it required enhancements)? 

http://docs.pylonsproject.org/projects/colander/en/latest/"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-12-06 01:26:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Doug,

I can't provide you with a list of things that were considered and a list of reasons why each of those things were insufficient or not extendable to do what we want. We wrote up a plan of things that we wanted the model to do and sent it to the openstack-dev mailing list asking for feedback:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-May/008641.html

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ObjectProposal

We had some initial prototype-y code for people to look at, a little discussion on the mailing list, a lot of discussion on IRC and at the summit that kicked off the idea. We set out from there to solve a specific batch of problems for Nova with this and it continues to work very well for us. You could certainly make the argument that the other projects who have already picked this up (or are hoping to) could use something more general like colander, but I think Nova is pretty committed at this point.

I think colander is pretty focused on serialization and schema verification, which is only part of what Nova gains from its object model. Magic remoting and versioning being the most obvious of what isn't covered by colander, that I can see from a quick glance. I'm sure the versioning bit could be added, or wrapped around the core. I'm not sure that anything RPC-related is in the scope if colander, and it may be that it too could be bolted on as well.

--Dan"}, {'account_id': 9124, 'date': '2013-12-08 22:26:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There are two concepts motivating this patch.

First, a move away from the DBAPI pattern (fat interface with all persistence code behind a single API) towards a set of base object interfaces with default SQLAlchemy implementations.  The new interfaces would have appropriately coarse methods on the objects for handling transactional changes (doSomethingComplexAllAtOnce) that would allow a 3rd party to implement a separate persistence backend.  For that, this commit introduces only the registry.

The second problem is simple versioned remotability without client code having to explicitly make that decision, and Dan has covered that above.  The serialization library does seem like something that could be replaced over time in a backward-compatible way, although it would require the library to talk to OpenStack RPC.  I guess I would also ask whether Colander can deliver significant benefits over the existing Nova implementation - I don't know Nova well, but I'd say no, and Nova's use case is a superset of most other project's needs."}, {'account_id': 9124, 'date': '2013-12-09 15:41:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-09 15:45:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-oslo-incubator-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/76/60376/2/check/gate-oslo-incubator-pep8/8085b51 : SUCCESS in 2m 10s
- gate-oslo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/76/60376/2/check/gate-oslo-incubator-docs/a331317/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 45s
- gate-oslo-incubator-python26 http://logs.openstack.org/76/60376/2/check/gate-oslo-incubator-python26/53320dd : SUCCESS in 3m 22s
- gate-oslo-incubator-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/76/60376/2/check/gate-oslo-incubator-python27/590f3e8 : SUCCESS in 3m 50s
'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2013-12-09 23:02:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Doug, please revisit this patch. The build error has been addressed. The plan here is to iterate on this code rather than merging https://review.openstack.org/57023 into the Solum code base we are following your guidance from http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-December/021203.html'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-12-12 16:51:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So, I think I'm good with this going into Oslo.  It's already in heavy use in Nova and it's being hand copied to other projects (see the referenced https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57022/) which is exactly what we're trying to avoid with Oslo.  And as Dan mentions, this code does quite a bit more than what colander claims to, so it doesn't sound like a full replacement (although maybe colander could be leveraged for part of this functionality in the future?  Just spitballing)

That said, this is an 1100+ line patch, which makes it basically impossible to review properly, and only appears to have partial test coverage.  I see tests for fields but nothing for base.  Maybe base is entirely covered by the fields tests, but that doesn't feel very unit-y if so.

In short, I would like to see this split up a bit if possible (since it's a copy of reviewed, working code I'm not necessarily looking for the magic < 200 line mark, but < 1100 would be nice ;-), and to have full test coverage before it merges into Oslo."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-12-12 20:27:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sorry for the delay in getting back to this. I was traveling, and am out sick today. I'll try to take another, closer, look tomorrow. In the mean time:

I do understand that this does more than serialization, but that's not an argument for ignoring prior art on that aspect. Are the serialization, remote RPC, and versioning so tightly coupled that we couldn't address that detail?

I'll be interested to see the response to Ben's request to split up the patch, too."}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2013-12-13 19:59:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

With respect, it's not reasonable to expect Clayton to rewrite a bunch of this code to use colander. We are contributing this here to allow easy reuse by other projects. It has been in use within Nova and Ironic for some time now, and we want to re-use it in Solum. We are getting resistance to putting it in our project because we would be perpetuating the problem of too many copies of this getting maintained separately. My suggestion is to merge this as-is, and if further simplification can be done, address those as iterations on this code. The reason we copied this code from Nova is because we did not want to re-implement prior art. commit_message:
Provide common objects abstraction

This work is based on the Nova and Ironic objects code and introduces an
object type registry mapping interfaces to implementations, common
primitive hydration, and explicit field declaration with type coercion
between primitive formats to python formats.

Imported nova/objects/base.py and nova/objects/fields.py from nova commit
93efad46aa1cbb9aef68561aca49278ef7584983.

* Renamed Object to DomainObject for better clarity
* Split metataclass behavior and core methods, added register_obj_class(),
  reset_obj_classes(), and obj_class_for_name() to allow easier subclassing
  by complex objects.
* Removed RPC logic (will replace the @remotable syntax with oslo.messaging
  as necessary)
* Removed Nova specific field types

The base code here is now easier to use with subclasses (allowing a consumer
to load and register their own implementations of the base classes)

Moved from https://review.openstack.org/57022 on request to enable shared
use.

Change-Id: Iee91194cc20fa8ea44790b9c9684f95fd0eec8aa

commit_message:
memory and cpu amount parameters for each slave node

it was impossible to specify memory and cpu amount values for each slave node.
All slave nodes were identical. But for future cases  we need to have nodes with 2GB+ RAM.
The patch splits HARDWARE parameter to ADMIN_NODE_HARDWARE and SLAVE_NODES_HARDWARE (list)

Change-Id: I60f1324e36a171fc7047a06c8777e94d8a8927b8

[{'created': '2013-12-18 06:07:32.000000000', 'message': "Don't do XML decoding if the type isn't known

There are routes that require a specific Content-Type to be returned and
if they pass through the XML decoding middleware it will fail as it
doesn't check that what it is receiving is the JSON that it expects.

In the event that it is not JSON data we should attempt to load it (in
case it's a python dictionary) but otherwise we should simply pass it
through and return a non-XML response rather than an error in JSON.

Change-Id: Ia6c7c4a029f6d41278f61f1a00b9d10375ec91d0
Closes-Bug: #1262057
"}]
commit_message:
Don't do XML decoding if the type isn't known

There are routes that require a specific Content-Type to be returned and
if they pass through the XML decoding middleware it will fail as it
doesn't check that what it is receiving is the JSON that it expects.

In the event that it is not JSON data we should attempt to load it (in
case it's a python dictionary) but otherwise we should simply pass it
through and return a non-XML response rather than an error in JSON.

Change-Id: Ia6c7c4a029f6d41278f61f1a00b9d10375ec91d0
Closes-Bug: #1262057

commit_message:
Ensure memcached_servers used by memcache is a list

Memorycache argument expect a list of memcache servers, but when we first
try get memcached_servers from self.conf, it's not a list. this patch fixes
that case.

Closes-Bug: 1261260

Change-Id: I5b824dfd5fc98f20506c982022912c9b41907f15
