commit_message:
Make libvirt ephemeral storage cache type configurable

The cache type used for volume storage is configurable since long,
but we did not have an option for the ephemeral storage.

The "none" cache type does not have the best performance with every
storage setup, however it provides the best chances to survive a power
outage.
Let the users the pick cache type which fits to their requirements.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I3b03862a1037b931948c8c464cbebc67fe3538f2

commit_message:
Simplify security group search logic

This will also speed up search since encoding is moved out of the
the loop. Also, getting all security groups is done only once.
The code to check if multiple matches are found is dead since
nova does not allow creating multiple security groups with same name
Thus there is no need to write another test to check NoUniqueMatch
exception.

Closes-Bug: #1254945

Change-Id: I0185116a60b2c5214f13f6b999683bbae8708e9a

commit_message:
Vol-transfer Creation doesn't support 'name' via xml

Volume-transfer creation can specify the 'name' param.
That's true via json format, everything's ok.
But when you create it via xml format, the 'name' param is not effective.

The problem caused by the deserializer.

But the cinderclient uses 'name' param, so this modification will effect the cin
 derclient..
If I change the 'display_name' to 'name' in xml deserializer,
 that won't need to midify the cinderclient.

I checked the original codes of api & db for v-transfer,
 it seems that 'display_name' should be the desired/correct one.

So I incline to modify it like this.

Fixes bug: 1243613

Change-Id: I05e41739edb8bcc2a6d677f22d11b07bf36b99a7

commit_message:
Allow setting Keystone API version in service catalog

This is the first step toward removing the Identity API version from the
Service Catalog, by setting IDENTITY_API_VERSION="" in local.conf
no version is added to the Identity Service Catalog URLs.

This _will_ break the current clients but is useful for testing
API version discovery.

Change-Id: I4870cddcb75488b3b6837a15b063aa69cdcc1444

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-06 01:55:08.000000000', 'message': "Fixes invalid error message when uploading objects

Swift client reports error when uploading object with a
non-admin user with correct write ACL. Error is reported
due to the fact that before attempting to upload, swift
will attempt to put a container in case it doesn't exist.

When the container already exists, it will just report an
expected error for non-admin users, because they don't
have the necessary ACLs to perform a HEAD on containers.

This fix just ignores the 403 error to not confuse non-admin
users.

Closes-Bug: 1204558
Change-Id: I0e1bc2f475beda954af39d680454f37435fc2d6a
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiagodasilva@gmail.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes invalid error message when uploading objects

Swift client reports error when uploading object with a
non-admin user with correct write ACL. Error is reported
due to the fact that before attempting to upload, swift
will attempt to put a container in case it doesn't exist.

When the container already exists, it will just report an
expected error for non-admin users, because they don't
have the necessary ACLs to perform a HEAD on containers.

This fix just ignores the 403 error to not confuse non-admin
users.

Closes-Bug: 1204558
Change-Id: I0e1bc2f475beda954af39d680454f37435fc2d6a
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiagodasilva@gmail.com>

[{'created': '2013-12-15 01:05:14.000000000', 'message': 'Have tox install via setup.py develop

tox 1.6 was released, which means that we can now take advantage of
the feature we added to it - which is using setup.py develop to
install the code into the virtualenv. The logic was taken from
run_tests.sh - so the performance issues around using tox vs. using
install_venv should now be gone.

Additionally, override the tox pip install command to avoid using
the "--pre" option which is the default in tox. "--pre" means
"Include pre-release and development versions." By default, pip will
only install stable versions of software, and that is the behavior
we want.

Change-Id: Ida5e440d1bdb9f8e9031277ea53a02d2ef171438
Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Have tox install via setup.py develop

tox 1.6 was released, which means that we can now take advantage of
the feature we added to it - which is using setup.py develop to
install the code into the virtualenv. The logic was taken from
run_tests.sh - so the performance issues around using tox vs. using
install_venv should now be gone.

Additionally, override the tox pip install command to avoid using
the "--pre" option which is the default in tox. "--pre" means
"Include pre-release and development versions." By default, pip will
only install stable versions of software, and that is the behavior
we want.

Change-Id: Ida5e440d1bdb9f8e9031277ea53a02d2ef171438
Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>

commit_message:
add/removeTenantAccess throws 500 Error in v2 api

The function addTenantAccess and removeTenantAccess don't check whether
the parameter "tenant" is in request body. So the 500 error has been
thrown. Modify the code, to throw 400(HttpBadRequest).

Change-Id: I1fe864f948732c8ca2d976f6727d2087459ed6fc
Closes-Bug: 1253014

2, The link below said "Many of the older performance benchmarks that have shown MySQL to be much faster than PostgreSQL"

The thruth however, from this and other bugs, is that Neutron IPAM has not been designed with multiple servers in mind.

This patch, while fixing the failure issue with a retry mechanism, will probably leave us with incosistent ip availability ranges.
Looking at the two operations in the committ message, the final result should be first_ip=192.168.1.15 - which is fine. But with the retry mechanism there's little guaranteed about the actual order, so the final result might be as well first_ip=192.168.1.16"}, {'account_id': 2711, 'date': '2013-08-27 03:53:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

hi Salvatore, in my mind:

Assume at the beginning there is a availability range 192.168.1.16 - 192.168.1.20, two neutron servers first allocate ip 192.168.1.16 and then free ip 192.168.1.15
if using the retry mechanism of this patch there's guaranteed about the actual order:
1) allocate ip 192.168.1.16, will because: 192.168.1.17 - 192.168.1.20
2) free ip 192.168.1.15, will because: 192.168.1.15 - 192.168.1.15,  and 192.168.1.17 - 192.168.1.20

but if still use present wrong logic, the result will be: 192.168.1.15 - 192.168.1.20 or 192.168.1.17 - 192.168.1.20

so I think this patch will work well to fix this bug, could you give some examples for your concern that probably leave us with incosistent ip availability ranges ?"}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-08-27 03:58:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-22 11:46:03.000000000', 'message': "Fix a race condition about IPAvailabilityRange

If there are multiple neutron-servers concurrently
executing allocate/free ip call, a race condition
can occur.
Suppose that I have 2 neutron-servers running,
one gets a request to allocate 192.168.1.16 and
the other gets a request to free 192.168.1.15.
Both servers are going to generate UPDATEs to the
DB, they will look something like this:
SERVER 1: UPDATE ipavailabilityranges SET first_ip
   = '192.168.1.17' WHERE first_ip = '192.168.1.16'
SERVER 2: UPDATE ipavailabilityranges SET first_ip
   = '192.168.1.15' WHERE first_ip = '192.168.1.16'

One solution is to use distributed lock,
unfortunately, oslo doesn't have this feature now.
We had to resort to the database, using long
transaction combinating with 'select for update'
to lock the whole table to ensure two transaction
are excuted linearly insteading of setting
transaction isolation level serializable.
'select for update' will work well with left
join in postgresql as well since all fields of
ipallocationpools are not null (can refer 1191653).

BTW, exsiting unittest has covered this case.

Change-Id: Ia06df25dec40f6ab3ec61c3db9bb9c343c1f4193
Closes-Bug: #1214115
"}, {'created': '2013-08-23 15:23:11.000000000', 'message': "Fix a race condition about IPAvailabilityRange

If there are multiple neutron-servers concurrently
executing allocate/free ip call, a race condition
can occur.
Suppose that I have 2 neutron-servers running,
one gets a request to allocate 192.168.1.16 and
the other gets a request to free 192.168.1.15.
Both servers are going to generate UPDATEs to the
DB, they will look something like this:
SERVER 1: UPDATE ipavailabilityranges SET first_ip
   = '192.168.1.17' WHERE first_ip = '192.168.1.16'
SERVER 2: UPDATE ipavailabilityranges SET first_ip
   = '192.168.1.15' WHERE first_ip = '192.168.1.16'

One solution is to use distributed lock,
unfortunately, oslo doesn't have this feature now.
We had to resort to the database, using long
transaction combinating with 'select for update'
to lock the whole table to ensure two transaction
are excuted linearly insteading of setting
transaction isolation level serializable.
'select for update' will work well with left
join in postgresql as well since all fields of
ipallocationpools are not null (can refer 1191653).

BTW, exsiting unittest has covered this case.

and there is no doubt that table lock will have a
certain influence on the performance, but it should
be the most important before finding a better way.

Change-Id: Ia06df25dec40f6ab3ec61c3db9bb9c343c1f4193
Closes-Bug: #1214115

commit_message:
Fix a race condition about IPAvailabilityRange

If there are multiple neutron-servers concurrently
executing allocate/free ip call, a race condition
can occur.
Suppose that I have 2 neutron-servers running,
one gets a request to allocate 192.168.1.16 and
the other gets a request to free 192.168.1.15.
Both servers are going to generate UPDATEs to the
DB, they will look something like this:
SERVER 1: UPDATE ipavailabilityranges SET first_ip
   = '192.168.1.17' WHERE first_ip = '192.168.1.16'
SERVER 2: UPDATE ipavailabilityranges SET first_ip
   = '192.168.1.15' WHERE first_ip = '192.168.1.16'

One solution is to use distributed lock,
unfortunately, oslo doesn't have this feature now.
We had to resort to the database, using long
transaction combinating with 'select for update'
to lock the whole table to ensure two transaction
are excuted linearly insteading of setting
transaction isolation level serializable.
'select for update' will work well with left
join in postgresql as well since all fields of
ipallocationpools are not null (can refer 1191653).

BTW, exsiting unittest has covered this case.

and there is no doubt that table lock will have a
certain influence on the performance, but it should
be the most important before finding a better way.

Change-Id: Ia06df25dec40f6ab3ec61c3db9bb9c343c1f4193
Closes-Bug: #1214115

commit_message:
test 3 date format in functional tests

According to HTTP/1.1, servers MUST accept all three formats:

Sun, 06 Nov 1994 08:49:37 GMT     # RFC 822, updated by RFC 1123
Sunday, 06-Nov-94 08:49:37 GMT    # RFC 850, obsoleted by RFC 1036
Sun Nov 6 08:49:37 1994           # ANSI C's asctime() format

In functional tests, a date value header has 3 kinds of format will be
tested.

Change-Id: I679ed44576208f2a79bffce787cb55bda4b39705
Closes-Bug: #1253207

Hi Sean,

I discovered this bug when I added some tests for the floating ips, here is the review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56349/
I didn't want to mix the bug fixing with the test addition, that's why I created two patches.
This problem wasn't discovered before because no test was accessing the field 'fixed_ips' directly, which I do in my patch 56349.
I realized the fixed_ips was correctly serialized as an array for the JSON test, so I could do fixed_ips[0] to get the first one. While for xml tests it was serialized as a dictionary.
Hope this solves your doubts otherwise let me know."}, {'account_id': 6788, 'date': '2013-12-11 18:25:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-12-11 18:25:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Serialize plurals correctly in neutron xml client

'fixed_ips' and others were incorrectly serialized as dict instead
of arrays

Change-Id: Id50039d158d3f547d72296064a2187fbf90831fe
Closes-Bug: #1255969

Previously, DHCP notifications for which active agents could not
be found were silently dropped.  This change ensures that
notifications are sent to scheduled agents even if those agents do
not appear to be active.  Further, notifications for which an
active agent can not be found will result in an exception.

This change is required because the Neutron service, when under
load, may not be able to process agent heartbeats in a timely
fashion and will then incorrectly presume that a given agent is
down.

It is safe to send a notification to an agent erroneously reported
as being down, and subsequent patches will ensure that it is safe
to send a notification to an agent that is actually down.

Closes-bug: #1192381
Change-Id: Id3e639d9cf3d16708fd66a4baebd3fbeeed3dde8

be active.

Additionally, if no agent is scheduled for a given network, an

commit_message:
Send DHCP notifications regardless of agent status

The Neutron service, when under load, may not be able to process
agent heartbeats in a timely fashion.  This can result in
agents being erroneously considered inactive.  Previously, DHCP
notifications for which active agents could not be found were
silently dropped.  This change ensures that notifications for
a given network are sent to agents even if those agents do not
appear to be active.

Additionally, if no enabled dhcp agents can be found for a given
network, an error will be logged.  Raising an exception might be
preferable, but has such a large testing impact that it will be
submitted as a separate patch if deemed necessary.

Partial-bug: #1192381
Change-Id: Id3e639d9cf3d16708fd66a4baebd3fbeeed3dde8

subject: Neutron: create network resources when agents are started

commit_message:
Neutron: create network resources when agents are started

Creating network resources before the agents start with the ml2
plugin might result in bnding failures for some resources such as
DHCP ports because the resources are created before the agents
report to the server.

This patch should ensure all agents have started and reported
their state to the server before creating network resources.

Change-Id: Ifafb73bd3c5409a555a573ad9a94b96d79061c38
Related-Bug: #1253896

 * SQLAlchemy error patterns improved
 * Remove unused import

commit_message:
Update oslo-incubator db.sqlalchemy module

Changes -
 * Use hacking import_exceptions for gettextutils._
 * Add docstring for exception handlers of session
 * Removal of _REPOSITORY global variable.
 * Remove string.lowercase usage
 * Database hook enabling traditional mode at MySQL
 * Replace xrange in for loop with range
 * SQLAlchemy error patterns improved
 * Remove unused import
 * Correct invalid docstrings
 * Remove start index 0 in range()
 * Make _extra_keys a property of ModelBase

commit_message:
Support remote VM hosts in boot-seed-vm.

With the upcoming test cluster, we need the ability to boot seed VMs
that are stored on a remote machine. This involves copying the image
onto the machine, chattr +C'ing it and then calling virsh start with
an appropriate URI.

Change-Id: I6194ad94d96aec08105f11acfae61b674a6f15c0

[{'created': '2013-12-23 02:49:52.000000000', 'message': "Remove ceilometer from the grenade gate

Ceilometer doesn't have a grenade upgrade script so if it is installed
by devstack on the old run then having the middleware in the pipeline
means the old version will also be imported on the new run. This can
lead to conflicting requirements.

Change-Id: Ifac7f5df5f6ac013b065e4dc4b582bee7a30d923
Closes-bug: #1262934
"}]
commit_message:
Remove ceilometer from the grenade gate

Ceilometer doesn't have a grenade upgrade script so if it is installed
by devstack on the old run then having the middleware in the pipeline
means the old version will also be imported on the new run. This can
lead to conflicting requirements.

Change-Id: Ifac7f5df5f6ac013b065e4dc4b582bee7a30d923
Closes-bug: #1262934

commit_message:
Add common::set_endpoints_by_interface & common::sysctl to os-base role

These recipes are part of the openstack-common cookbook and are managed
completely by optional attributes, so they do not affect the existing behavior.

commit_message:
Nexenta iSCSI driver: use one iSCSI target and group config option

Adds special config option that force using single iSCSI target and
group for Cinder volumes created on NexentaStor appliance volume.

This helps users avoid NexentaStor appliance 255 iSCSI targets
limitiation.

Change-Id: Icb64989bc04deb0eaa5e57c77766ee6ec3e2a67f

[{'created': '2013-12-23 13:26:47.000000000', 'message': "prune grenade service lists to things we can upgrade

We should only install services in grenade that we know how to
upgrade, otherwise we can run into an issue where we install a
service on the old side, it injects some code using entry points
into other projects, we don't upgrade it, it breaks that service
from upgrading. aka: ceilometer.

We really should have a policy that we only enable services in
grenade that we are going to upgrade. It also calls out nicely
which services those *aren't*.

This patch also does some normalization of the service lists since
we no longer need to support folsom, so cinder and swift should
always be enabled. There is probably a more clever service selector
that could be done here, but this is at least more straight forward
for reviewing.

Change-Id: I4e3975d74082f99b8f13d99a0865886b0e462ae3
"}]
commit_message:
prune grenade service lists to things we can upgrade

We should only install services in grenade that we know how to
upgrade, otherwise we can run into an issue where we install a
service on the old side, it injects some code using entry points
into other projects, we don't upgrade it, it breaks that service
from upgrading. aka: ceilometer.

We really should have a policy that we only enable services in
grenade that we are going to upgrade. It also calls out nicely
which services those *aren't*.

This patch also does some normalization of the service lists since
we no longer need to support folsom, so cinder and swift should
always be enabled. There is probably a more clever service selector
that could be done here, but this is at least more straight forward
for reviewing.

Change-Id: I4e3975d74082f99b8f13d99a0865886b0e462ae3

commit_message:
Allow running just one test with tox

Now, "tox -e py26 -- test.unit.proxy.test_server" runs just that one
test file.

"tox -e py26" still runs all the tests with py26, just like before.

Change-Id: I40db12dd5e7cc8f9388e29b30447f70d3bfc4b28

Package resources can no longer have array for name since Puppet 3.4.

Since the package nova-novncproxy already requires novnc,
we can safely remove it from the list of packages to install.

Closes-bug: #1263293
Change-Id: Iba7ff0b7aedd750a54d931e0e8cbe37418ed6aed
'}]
commit_message:
Remove novnc from vncproxy packages list for Ubuntu

Package resources can no longer have array for name since Puppet 3.4.

Since the package nova-novncproxy already requires novnc,
we can safely remove it from the list of packages to install.

Closes-bug: #1263293
Change-Id: Iba7ff0b7aedd750a54d931e0e8cbe37418ed6aed

commit_message:
Use database_ prefix for database parameters

A prefix is required to avoid any confusion about
the purpose of those parameters.

puppet-nova uses database_ for those parameters. It makes sense
to use the same in puppet-ironic.

This change breaks backward compatibility.

Change-Id: Id78f5c41a7d0ab0e9fe2430d1f8b9a2cc6a66e05

commit_message:
Remove use of deprecated include_class matcher

include_class is deprecated since rspec-puppet 1.0.0.
contain_class should be used instead.

Closes-bug: #1263617
Change-Id: I0915f843e9fb35e94651498064ae12d00f6360d3

commit_message:
Adding IDH plugin basic implementation

Functionality:

* install and provision Intel Hadoop Manager and Intel Hadoop
* configure Intel Hadoop to use Cinder volumes as HDFS backend
* manual cluster scaling support
* Swift integration
* cluster configs - the same configs as in Vanilla Hadoop
* configs validation - the same as in Vanilla plugin

This is continuation of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56105

This is initial version. It doesn't cover bugs filed here:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/savanna/+bugs?field.searchtext=%7BIDH%5D

Co-Authored-By: Joseph D Natoli <joseph.d.natoli@intel.com>

Implements blueprint idh-savanna-plugin

Change-Id: I23e1fe957e67723ab7011320d0a2b82256695e84

commit_message:
add support for working with pre-datastore instances

Old instances may not have a datastore or datastore version
defined, and the migration process will be highly vendor-specific,
so we need to make sure everything still works as much as possible
with those instances.

Change-Id: Iee5c3ad02c36e10a42937500b0252d913d97b708
Closes-Bug: #1259642

fwiw I find the script names a bit misleading -

Also, +1 to James suggestion, (we had something similar with the '-n' being removed from boot-seed-vm - though that was for starting the VM). I had to go look at the scripts again and see what's being called where (i.e. vm being defined in devtest.sh via setup-seed-vm and then started in devtest-seed.sh; in fact devtest-seed.sh starts with "*Create* and start your VM"'}, {'account_id': 6449, 'date': '2013-12-23 15:04:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

@Marios, James - the logic is deliberately *not* in 'seed' - because I want a clear separation between 'define' and 'use' test environments, rather than conditional code within devtest_seed. There's probably some blurred lines we need to detangle to make production deployments still be straight forward, but even there this split is an improvement - consider folk that download images; the big all in one script is unwieldy for that case too.

As for the script names -yeah, we could stand to redo a bunch, but I chose setup-seed-vm to match setup-network, which is *also* a one-time-part-of-test-environment-definition operation: a different name right now would be inconsistent : happy for someone to do a renaming patch!"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-23 19:23:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-23 19:24:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Split seed VM configuring out to a new script.

We can't depend on creating the seed VM fresh in the gate environment
- we don't have permission to create VMs as that would let use create
arbitrary libvirt containers unless very carefully controlled.

Having a one-time operation is also a bit easier to reason about:
 - make the VM
 - later make images for it

At any point in time, the VM exists, rather than being deleted and
recreated.

Change-Id: I91e61fdb51afd33a31eb2d3cad01ba8ac019eb59

[{'created': '2013-12-19 20:45:24.000000000', 'message': 'Change default ephemeral FS to ext4.

The ext3 filesystem does orders of magnitude more I/O than ext4 in
mkfs - a brief benchmark showed 14m to make a 1TB ext3 filesystem
vs 7 seconds to make a 1TB ext4 filesystem, with the ext3 filesystem
doing upwards of 6GB I/O.

Since ext4 has been a default in all major Linux distributions for
a long time now - RHEL5 has it as default, for instance - there is
no reason to default to ext3: users that need ext3 can configure
that themselves.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I833356af81df743a63d4442d389be82bc25f3914
'}]
commit_message:
Change default ephemeral FS to ext4.

The ext3 filesystem does orders of magnitude more I/O than ext4 in
mkfs - a brief benchmark showed 14m to make a 1TB ext3 filesystem
vs 7 seconds to make a 1TB ext4 filesystem, with the ext3 filesystem
doing upwards of 6GB I/O.

Since ext4 has been a default in all major Linux distributions for
a long time now - RHEL5 has it as default, for instance - there is
no reason to default to ext3: users that need ext3 can configure
that themselves.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I833356af81df743a63d4442d389be82bc25f3914

commit_message:
Fix validation problems for compute-api

Running "xmllint --noent --noout --schema \
http://docs.rackspace.com/rackbook/wadl.xsd *.wadl", I noticed
a couple of errors that I fixed:
* Wrong URLs for docbook
* Missing declarations

commit_message:
Set volume_dd_blocksize configurable on per-driver basis

Allow volume_dd_blocksize config option to be configurable on a
per-driver basis.
This allows drivers used in multi-backend configurations
to define their own values. We port this to the LVM and block_device
drivers here but it can easily be ported to others as and when
needed.

DocImpact

partially implement bp: per-driver-config-for-utils-functions

Change-Id: Ice9e815f18e5ebf3727aab7d3a221acacb710cd4

commit_message:
Timeout devstack/tempest internally

Abort the run of the gate script within the wrap script
after a specified time (60 minutes by default).  The wrap
script will be able to proceed to copy log files as usual
in case of a timeout.

Remove xtrace option that slipped in during earlier
devstack-gate testing.

Change-Id: I000fae1365534b204ab27f2014ba64eabafc7584

commit_message:
Initialize iptables rules on initialization of MetadataManager

To avoid multiple initialization of iptables rules if there are a few
workers for metadata service, perform iptables configuration in
__init__() of MetadataManager.

Change-Id: I674c04f973318f06cbb98693f0a884c824af8748
Closes-Bug: #1097999

commit_message:
Heat test modified to support neutron subnets.

Added SubnetId attribute to the stack template,
implemented method for retrieving subnet-id if Neutron enabled,
create_stack, update_stack methods generalized to avoid
code duplication,

Change-Id: Ie58a9ad08fe620965405e30283170874ed52e725
Closes-Bug: #1262163

commit_message:
Set DIB_COMMON_ELEMENTS for devtest_overcloud.sh

DIB_COMMON_ELEMENTS is now expected by devtest_overcloud.sh for common
elements that should be in all images. Setting so that images include
pypi-openstack, pip-cache and stackuser.

Change-Id: I219875b1b0e943f0cdf45684a7ca06244c6107fa

commit_message:
Set DIB_COMMON_ELEMENTS in devtest_overcloud.sh

For the cd-overcloud devtest_overcloud.sh is being run standalone
outside of devtest.sh. So this needs to be set seperately. This should
be followed with a patch to t-i-e/elements/tripleo-cd/tripleo-cd.sh to
set an appropriate value.

Change-Id: Icf20b49956e43adb3631c2df491b3d98d9543c6b

During the disk partitioning pmanager runs pvcreate
which asks for confirmation on wiping out the volume
group if it is found there. There was another fix
which does dd to clean up all information about
all disk partionins, so pvcreate should not ask
anything. This patch adds '-y' option to pvcreate,
and it writes changes without asking questions,

"}]
commit_message:
Unconditionaly do pvcreate

During the disk partitioning pmanager runs pvcreate
which asks for confirmation on wiping out the volume
group if it is found there. There was another fix
which does dd to clean up all information about
all disk partionins, so pvcreate should not ask
anything. This patch adds '-y' option to pvcreate,
and it writes changes without asking questions,
so we can be double sure that installation won't
stuck under some other condition on this command.

Change-Id: I7368ce58fa54155664d59adedbfc0463f7d3a3ea

subject: Update to point to wadls in the api-site repo to correct neutron:type error
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-15 16:23:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-noop http://logs.openstack.org/74/51874/1/check/gate-noop/6f81c6b : SUCCESS in 1s
'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-10-19 11:07:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm fine with switching to wadl for representing API operations.
There are some information which will be lost; for instance 'bulk operations', or details regarding the subnet IP allocation logic.

I can think of two alternatives: either update the WADL with these info (and dealing with the problem again when they'll be autogenerated) or add a new chapter "Using the Openstack Networking API" where all these information would be contained.

commit_message:
BigSwitch: Fixes floating IP backend updates

Changes BigSwitch plugin to correctly use
admin context on floating IP updates to the
backend controller so they correctly contain
floating IPs for all tenants.

Closes-Bug: #1262488
Change-Id: I6f2666c242e6d9b0684943db073a2284d01fa1e0

commit_message:
Setting the xen vm device id on vm record

Currently, while setting the device_id, the hypervisor
version is being incorrectly handled since the method
get_major_minor_version expects either an int, float,
or string format. However, the xen hypervisor
version is stored in the session product_version as a tuple.
This fix correctly uses the version to set the appropriate
device_id on the vm record. Also, removing the method
get_major_minor_version as it is not needed anymore.

Closes-bug: #1260178

Change-Id: I6b1353cdb7cc856b34f02e3d3679c142ba032533

hi Alex:
thanks for your review.
Yes, I also think this is not the best way to handle this bug.

But, if we return the content-type in https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/wsgi.py#L842 ,

The empty body will be deserialized. It will catch exception in
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/wsgi.py#L957
in this case , it's ok. But if some guys input a GET request to any resource  with "Content-Type: application/json", it will always return the exception:
"Malformed request body".

And in this case, if we want to pass the empty body to controller, the  deserializer should deserialize the empty body
to {"body": ""}. The GET request to any resource  with "Content-Type: application/json", it will always failed due to TypeError.(more parameters than required)

summary? It's ok, return content-type when there is no entity body in this case. But some side-effect arise. Issue GET request with "content-type",  will be always failed. Currently, it will be successful. Because it will ignore the unused option. Actually, I'm not sure the side-effect should be considered as another bug.'}, {'account_id': 5586, 'date': '2013-11-21 08:08:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
pass the empty body into the controller

This allows POST and PUT reqeusts without content-body. The
default body: None will be passed into the controller, and
will be validated in the controller, so it fixes the bug 1253089.

When the request method is GET or DELETE, the content-type
and body in the request will be ignored
.
When POST or PUT a request with body but without content-type,
it will return "unsupported the content-type provided" with
response code 400.

side-effect: The method which handle the request method: POST
or PUT must have the parameter: body. Otherwise, it will raise:
"got an unexpected keyword argument 'body'"

And some tests are updated due to this change.
The parameter: body are also added for some actions which are
mapped to the method: POST or PUT.

Closes-bug: 1253089

commit_message:
Implement cancelling of stack update

This patch implements triggering of stack rollback upon receiving
`cancel` as `update_type` parameter of the stack update request.

Also implements `CancelUpdateStack` action of CFN API
using the above new functionality.

Change-Id: I87af9cfa2b010293e2b1dae8f943c58497839a76
Implements: blueprint cancel-update-stack

Helper should use admin net instead of internal

Use admin network to retrieve master node IP
in helper decorator which dumps commands needed
to revert environment and get access to the
master node

commit_message:
VMware: image aging support

Images that are unused will be marked for aging. These images
will be deleted after they have not been used for
'remove_unused_original_minimum_age_seconds'.

The third and final phase of blueprint vmware-image-cache-management.

Change-Id: Ie9f33a173e2f29e467348dfecb08f281c264c57e
